	   <tr><td colspan=2><br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;I accidentally left off my take on what new monks should spend their skill points on.<br><br> My advice is similar to that of Neige's...  You should focus on raising most of your skills through repetition rather than by expenditure(big word for a monk) of skillpoints. The reasoning behind this lies behind two words.... Feign Death.<br><br> Feign Death is the skill of skills. I cannot imagine any other skill being as useful as our FD skill. It is simply incredible and your life as a monk will be forever changed upon reaching that 17th circle. However, you will find that until your Feign Death skill approaches the 50's(possibly higher), your FD will fail and fail often. And trust me Feign Death is a skill that you usually can not afford to fail.<br><br>  For this reason I HIGHLY recommend that after 6th lvl you save nearly all of your skill points for Feign Death at lvl 17. The exception to this rule is for the points needed initially to learn a skill like Sneak at 8th. I've had absoultely no dificulty in raising my combat skills through combat alone, and very little difficulty in raising skills like Mend, Safe Fall, or Sneak by repetitive action. I believe this is partially due to my high Agility, however that is just my opinion; I have no proof. But FD did take awhile to raise to the point at which it was somewhat dependable, so use those skillpoints instead. Be aware that raising your skill in FD by @50 skillpoints is going to cost you a good amount of platinum. Well worth the price in my opinion.<br><br> Once again should any of my monkish brethren(or sisters) have any comments or corrections, please post.<br><br> Geiden Longfist<br> 25th monk of Karana<br><br> Geiden<br> 10th monk of Morrell-Thule<br><br>&nbsp;<br> "I like a man who grins when he fights..."<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;                                   - Winston Churchil</td></tr>
