<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=96658690319802></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96658690319802><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=96658690319802>RE: Starting stats and learning skills...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=96658690319802#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 4:21 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.85]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2><br>This advice is given for a human monk, I have never had a iksar monk so I can't comment on that.<br><br>Agility will determine how often your defensive combat skills like block, dodge, etc... will proc and also determines your base ac.&nbsp;&nbsp;Therefore agi is obviously a very important stat for monks because of the lack of hit points they have.  Also, at low lvls, 1 or 2 ac isn't much, but at higher lvls you notice it, believe it or not.  Another small piece of advice about agi...I see alot of young monks going for agi instead of ac equipment.  I must say that I made this mistake when I was younger too but then I realized, ac equipment will yeild better results than agi equipment will.  If you don't believe me, try it out and see for yourself.  I'm not saying you should scrap agi, agi is still a important stat, just don't neglect ac for it.  I suggest putting half of your skills into agi.<br><br>Dex determines how often your offensive combat skills proc, how often your weapon effects proc, and is supposed to determine how often you hit, (although I have never noticed a difference).  I would put maybe 1/3 of your remaining points into this.  I put half of mine in it and I am regretting it now.<br><br>Finally we come to strength.  Str for monks means one thing and one thing only, how hard you hit for.  The damage that monks can deliver is based in quick, fast, strikes for low amounts of damage, therefore when you increase str, you increase the amount of damage than each one of these strikes can do.  That is a significant increase in total damage and any monk that wishes to remain the king of undisputed melee damage would be wise to put at least, the remaining 2/3 of your points into str.  <br><br>Of course, there are individual cases where you may wish to distribute your points a little differently.  This is just my take on how to distribute your points.  I made my monk with half agi and half dex.  Now I wish I had more str instead of dex.<br><br>Zanshin Wuitang<br>35 monk prexus<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
